subsystems.name: Unreachable Dead Code Island
subsystems.purpose: Isolated code fragments with zero callers, hardwired-zero register sinks, and no return mechanisms—likely compiler artifacts, test stubs, or corrupted disassembly boundaries

subsystems.evidence_summary: All 11 functions share critical defects: zero callers in promoted execution set (60 functions, 2,536 instructions), high percentage of writes to hardwired-zero registers (r0, f0, f1), missing or invalid return mechanisms (no bri r1, abnormal fall-through, trap without context), and patterns inconsistent with known firmware structures (no r15 GState, no PostScript dispatch chains, no ABI-conformant prologues). Despite curated confidence sources, these functions appear unreachable from normal execution paths. Confidence capped at 25 due to lack of call graph integration and semantic incoherence (75-95% of instructions produce no observable effects).

control_flow_summary: The analyzed subset represents an execution-unreachable code island within the 795 KB kernel firmware. All 11 functions exhibit zero incoming call edges, preventing static determination of entry conditions. The dominant pattern is indirect branch (bri) through runtime-computed targets (r2, r3) classified as 'dynamic_entry' by Phase 2 analysis, confirming that dispatch addresses are ALU-chain computed and unresolvable without emulation. The absence of PostScript dispatch signatures (r15 GState, xorh 0x10c6 hash, and 0xe827 classify) and MMIO token reads (0x401C) outside isolated test sequences suggests these functions are not integrated into the primary threaded interpreter control flow. High sink-register write density (70-95% of instructions to r0/f0) combined with missing return mechanisms indicates these are either: (1) compiler/linker artifacts from dead code elimination failures, (2) embedded diagnostic stubs stripped from production call graph, or (3) corrupted disassembly boundaries at fat binary construction seams (m68k/x86 object overlap at 0x017CB8, 0x03DCB8, 0x05DCB8). The firmware's execution model remains opaque at this coverage level (1.4% of binary, 60/unknown total functions).

key_gaps: No call graph edges prevent subsystem boundary identification—all functions are isolated
No known firmware patterns (PostScript dispatch, r15 GState manipulation, MMIO 0x401C token read chains) matched in analyzed set
Zero callers in 60-function promoted execution set suggests analyzed functions are outside main kernel execution paths
MMIO register semantics unknown: 6 distinct MMIO offsets accessed but not cross-referenced with NeXTdimension hardware documentation
Indirect branch resolution blocked: 5 bri instructions with runtime-computed targets prevent control flow reconstruction
Data structure layouts unknown: byte table accesses, FP loads, and register-indexed memory operations lack type annotations
ABI conformance violations (r1/r2 misuse, missing returns, caller-saved register assumptions) prevent standard protocol inference
Missing: initialization sequences, main dispatcher entry point, interrupt vector table, known PostScript operator implementations
Curated confidence sources conflict with static analysis findings (no callers + no returns + sink writes = dead code, but flagged as execution-proven)
Requires: emulation traces, hardware register map, m68k/x86 relocation table analysis, Mach-O section boundary verification
